SIMPLE: acrylic
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: acrylic
<hw>a*cryl"ic</hw> <pr>(⟦adot⟧*kr⟦icr⟧l"⟦icr⟧k)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Of or containing <xex>acryl</xex>,
the hypothetical radical (<chform>R.CH:CH.CO-</chform>) of which
acrolein (<chform>H2C:CH.CHO</chform>) is the hydride; <as>as,
<ex>acrylic</ex> acid</as>. The characteristic residue in an acrylic
compound is the carbonyl group attached directly to an ethylenic
carbon.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to a derivative of acrylic acid, or
an object consisting mostly of an <er>acrylic resin</er>; <as>as, an
<ex>acrylic</ex> window</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Acrylic</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Acrylic
<hw>A*cryl"ic</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
paint in which the pigment is suspended in a solution of an <er>acrylic
resin</er>, which dries to a hard film on exposure to air.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A painting made using an acrylic paint; <as>as, he
donated several of his <ex>acrylics</ex> to the museum</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Same as <er>acrylic resin</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Same as <er>acrylic fiber</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Acrylic resin</ent>⟦br⟧
